## Implementation (pair programming / learning)

Use when extending a **service, app, library, or integration** in this repo. Complements **Change communication** above.

### Architecture (discover, do not assume)

Before large changes, infer structure from the repo: monorepo vs single package, API vs UI vs workers, data stores, and how components talk (REST, GraphQL, events, etc.). Document assumptions in summaries when the repo lacks a global diagram.

Example pattern (replace labels with your project):

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  subgraph clients [Clients]
    ClientA[Client apps]
  end
  subgraph services [Services]
    API[API / BFF]
    Core[Domain logic]
    Jobs[Workers / jobs]
    API --> Core
    Jobs --> Core
  end
  subgraph data [Data]
    DB[(Primary store)]
    Cache[(Cache / queue)]
  end
  Core --> DB
  API --> Cache
  Jobs --> Cache
  ClientA -->|protocol per spec| API
```

### Learning checkpoints (pair-programming pauses)

When the user asks to **pause after each phase or section** of a plan, work in **small batches**, stop after each agreed checkpoint, and explain **what** changed, **why** it matters, and **how to verify** (use that repo's documented dev/lint/test commands).

- **Default:** A plain **"execute"** may ship work in **larger batches**; still give high-level summaries per **Change communication**.
- **Checkpoint mode:** When the user says **"use the plan checkpoints"**, **"pause after each phase"**, or similar, follow the active plan file and **stop** after each checkpoint until they say **continue**.
- **Retrospective:** They can ask for a walkthrough **without new code** to map plan sections to files already in the repo.

If a plan file differs from this rule, **follow the plan** and update this rule when the checkpoint scheme changes.

